## Unit 1: Introduction and Secure Software Design

### Overview of Learning Focus

In Unit 1, the main objective was to understand foundational concepts in secure software development and how poor design decisions can introduce vulnerabilities early in the lifecycle. This included reviewing core security principles, modelling system behaviour using UML, and gaining awareness of the OWASP Top 10 risks that commonly affect web applications.

We explored how design documentation supports both usability and security, particularly by ensuring authentication, authorisation, and data handling processes are correctly implemented before any coding takes place.

---

### Secure UML Modelling Task

As part of the discussion activity, I created a UML Activity Diagram showing a **Broken Access Control** vulnerability path. This demonstrates a situation where a system correctly authenticates a user but fails to enforce authorisation checks before exposing protected resources.

This diagram supports OWASP A01:2021 guidance that access must be verified at every interaction with sensitive data.

üìå *Placeholder for diagram image. I will upload the PNG into the repository and link it here:*

`![Broken Access Control Activity Diagram](images/unit1-activity-diagram.png)`

I provided an initial discussion post analysing the weakness and recommended UML models to prevent it. I also responded constructively to two peers by suggesting enhancements to their diagrams and security flows.

